default&#xa0;defaultThe state’s positive obligation to investigate allegations of sladefaultvery, servitude, forced or compulsory labour (defaultCN v UKdefault)default&#xa0;
defaultThe Committee is particularly concerned with 
defaultthe state’s positive obligation to investigate allegations of slavery, servitude, forced or compulsory labour
default, as highlighted by the case CN v UK.  This is
default directly relevant to the treatment of people in prison who have been coerced or trafficked into offending. We are concerned that that the government is in breach of its obligations under existing international law.
default&#xa0;
defaultMany people who have been coerced or tr
defaultafficked into criminal behaviour are in prison either on remand or serving 
defaulta sentence. 
defaultWe welcome the recent announcement by the Home Secretary Theresa May of the Government’s intention to introduce an anti-slavery law which would make the organisation of 
defaultslavery an aggravated criminal offence.
default Too often it is the victims of human trafficking instead of the perpetrators who end up being prosecuted and imprisoned for offences 
defaultcommitted under the threat of violence
default and
default intimidation. 
default&#xa0;
defaultTwo reports, one 
defaultpublished by the Prison Reform Trust and Hibiscus,
default and the other by the University of Cambridge, 
defaultsupported by the Economic and Social Research Council,
default have underlined the lack of support available to 
defaultforeign national women in custody in England and Wale
defaults who have been trafficked into offending. The latter by Professor Loraine 
defaultGelsthorpe
default and Dr Liz Hales examines the case management of migrant women in the criminal justice and immigration systems, including the identification of trafficked 
defaultwomen. It found
default violence, intimidation and rape were common experiences of the women, but evidence of their suffering was often overlooked and they did not receive the protection guaranteed to them as victims of human trafficking under international law. In only one of t
defaulthe 43 cases of human trafficking identified by the researchers did victim disclosures result in a full police investigation in relation to the actions of the perpetrators.
default&#xa0;
defaultProtection for victims of human trafficking from prosecution relating to offences c
defaultommitted as a result of their being trafficked is enshrined in international agreements and domestic case law. The EU Directive on Trafficking, now in force, specifies that “Victims of trafficking in human beings should, in accordance with the basic princi
defaultples of the legal systems of the relevant Member States, be protected from prosecution or punishment for criminal activities such as the use of false documents, or offences under legislation on prostitution or immigration, that they have been compelled to 
defaultcommit as a direct consequence of being subject to trafficking.”
default The UN Protocol to Prevent Trafficking in Persons, Especially Women and Children, requires governments to ensure that trafficked persons are not punished for any offences or activities relat
defaulted to their having been trafficked (e.g. prostitution, immigration violations).
default In
default addition, the UNOHCHR (2002) Recommended Principles and Guidelines on Human Rights and Human Trafficking: Guideline 2 Paragraph 5, states: “Ensuring that trafficked persons
default are not prosecuted for violations of immigration laws or for the activities they are involved in as a direct consequence of their situation as trafficked persons.”
default&#xa0;
defaultA recent Court of Appeal decision 
defaultoverturning the convictions of 
defaultthree children and one ad
defaultult woman accepted that that there is a heavy onus on police and prosecutors to thoroughly investigate trafficking allegations so that unnecessary prosecutions do not happen, and that courts should stay prosecutions where there is evidence that the
default defenda
defaultnt may have been trafficked.
default  We would like to see this decision reflected more clearly in guidance and training for police, prosecution authorities and courts. The Criminal Case Review Commission should be encouraged to review the convictions of vulnerab
defaultle women and children in custody who may have been trafficked into offending. We also note and support the recent calls for improved care and support of children and young people who have been trafficked into offending.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe Prison Reform Trust and Hibisc
defaultus report 
defaultNo Way Out
default made a number of recommendations 
defaultthat
default 
defaultare of relevance:
default&#xa0;
defaultDeportation for foreign national prisoners and the right to family life (AA v UK) and lawful detention (defaultAbdidefault v UK)default&#xa0;
defaultC
defaulturrently deportation decisions are not based on real, 
defaultrelevant risk assessments that significantly take into account ind
defaultividual circumstances.  In AA v
default UK the 
defaultECtHR
default concluded that his risk of re-offending was low and “he had made commendable efforts to rehabilitate himself into society over a period of 7 years.”  There was also insufficient evidence to show that AA could reasonably be expected to engage 
defaultin further criminal activity, to make his deportation necessary “for the prevention of disorder or crime”
default.
default&#xa0;
defaultAll applications against deportation need to be considered on a case-by-case basis. The presumption that decisions taken within the Immigration Rule
defaults comply with Article 8 has led to a view that if proportionality has already been demonstrated at a general level, it need not be re-determined in every individual case. However, many people convicted of low-level offences are deported, breaching their ri
defaultghts to family and private life and causing immeasurable distress to themselves
default and their families.
default&#xa0;
defaultAs AA shows, individual assessment is necessary to ensure that the Government is complying with 
defaultArticle 
default8. Proportionality is not clearly defined and detai
defaultled guidance is needed. Under the new rules almost every foreign national prisoner is considered suitable for deportation regardless of the crime, risk of further offending, age at time of offence, time in the UK and family connections. Immigration service
default officers do not know how to assess risk of harm or whether deportation is in the public good.
default&#xa0;
defaultIn order for people to exercise their rights, legal aid for family rights cases need to be reinstated. Recent legal aid cuts severely limit access to justice fo
defaultr family law and 
defaultdeportation cases. This means that even people who have a strong case cannot access free legal advice to access their human rights. The Prison Reform Trust were recently contacted by a man in prison who explained that UKBA had told him his
default deportation complied with Article 8 because he was able to maintain contact with his baby in the UK through Skype
default.
default&#xa0;
defaultFollowing the decisions in 
defaultAbdi
default, the Secretary of State should issue new guidance to the immigration services relating to ongoing detention
default.  Firstly, people detained for immigration purposes should have a meaningful review monthly in accordance with the regulations. Currently, this is a perfunctory tick box exercise. Secondly, people who are detained pending deportation to countries that the
defaulty cannot be deported to should be immediately reviewed 
defaultfor assessment
default for bail or unconditional release. Thirdly, the practice of detention in prison for people post sentence should be stopped. Prison is not an appropriate environment for detainees.
default&#xa0;
defaultPrisodefaultner votingdefault (defaultHirstdefault vdefault UKdefault, defaultHirstdefault (No.2)default,default and Greens and M.Tdefault)default&#xa0;defaultFollowing the judgment of the European Court of Human Rights in 
defaultHirst
default v
default UK
default 
defaultin 2005, it has been repeatedly highlighted that the automatic and indiscriminate ban on all convicted offenders, barring 
defaultthose on remand or in custody on default, does not comply with Article 3 Protocol 1 of the European Convention on Human Rights 1950. Despite that judgment, which called for the UK to amend its position according to the convention, successive governments ha
defaultve delayed taking action to implement reform
default, largely for political reasons. 
default&#xa0;
defaultHighlighting his concerns with the current situation, Dean 
defaultSpielmann
default, President of the European Court of Human Rights, said “I observe with the deepest dismay the lack of any si
defaultgnificant progress in executing this judgment.”
default&#xa0;
defaultSuccessive UK Governments have justified the ban on the grounds that it prevents crime and punishes offenders, whilst enhancing civic responsibility and respect 
defaultfor the law. However, the 
defaultECtHR
default:
default&#xa0;
defaultfound no 
defaultevidence to support the claim that disenfranchisement deterred crime and considered that the imposition of a punishment on all prisoners regardless of their crime or individual circumstances indicated no rational link between the punishment and the offende
defaultr.
default&#xa0;
defaultIn fact, the 
defaultECtHR
default continue
defaults, removal of the right to vote:
default&#xa0;
defaultruns counter to the rehabilitation of the offender as a law abiding member of the community and undermines the authority of the law as derived from a legislature which the community as a who
defaultle votes into power.
default&#xa0;defaultThe 
defaultcurrent 
defaultban 
defaultserves
default no purpose. It neither protects public safety, nor acts as an effective deterrent. It does not function as a means to correct the behaviour of offenders and does not assist in their rehabilitation. It is not ar
defaultticulated at the point of sentence and 
defaultbears no relation to the crime committed and so is an additional and arbitrary punishment. Following the principle of “just deserts”, to make the punishment fit the crime, it would be appropriate to strip offenders of
default their voting rights in cases of electoral fraud.
default&#xa0;
defaultWhilst
default the establishment of the 
defaultJoint Select Committee on the Draft Voting Eligibility (Prisoners) Bill
default marks a step forward
default, it is disappointing that the draft bill includes a proposal to retain the curre
defaultnt ban. The Committee of Ministers noted “
defaultthe third option [in the Bill] aimed at retaining the blanket restriction criticised by the European Court cannot be considered compatible with the European Convention on Human Rights”.
default 
defaultIt is 
defaultalso 
defaultregrettable that
default all three options retain an automatic ban on some sentenced prisoners, regardless of their particular offence.
default&#xa0;
defaultWe call for two further options to be considered:
default&#xa0;
defaultThis second option has been adopted in a number of Council of Europe countries, including France, Germany and Belgium and has been mooted by MPs and peers in parliamentary debat
defaultes. The UK has been given a sufficiently wide margin of appreciation for Parliament to decide on the best way to implement reform. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThere would be few problems in extending the franchise to prisoners. The Electoral Commission already has mechanisms in pla
defaultce for remand prisoners to vote and identifies them as “hard to reach voters” with whom it is important to engage.
